[[Image:Trinity tower.jpg|250px|right|thumb|The tower used in the [[Trinity test]], 1945.]]
A '''bomb tower''' is a lightly constructed [[tower]], often 100 to 700 feet (30 to 210 meters) high, built to hold a [[nuclear weapon]] for an above ground [[nuclear testing|nuclear test]]. The tower holds the bomb for the purpose of the investigation of its destructive effects (such as [[burst height]] and distance with given [[nuclear weapon yield|explosive yield]]) and for the adjustment of measuring instruments, such as [[high-speed camera]]s. Normally, the bomb tower disintegrates completely on detonation due to the enormous heat of the explosion.

