[[File:Swim diaper (1335216873).jpg|right|thumb|250px|Packages of swim diapers (left)]]
A '''swim diaper''' is a [[diaper]] that is made for those who are [[Fecal incontinence|incontinent]], usually babies or young children, which is worn underneath a [[bathing suit]], or as a bathing suit. Swim diapers can be reusable and disposable. They are not intended to be absorbent.<ref name="Pull-Ups® and Swim Diapers are Not the Same Thing">{{cite web|last1=Schultz|first1=Hollie|title=Pull-Ups® and Swim Diapers are Not the Same Thing|url=https://www.babygizmo.com/pull-ups-and-swim-diapers-are-not-the-same-thing/|publisher=Baby Gizmo|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> Typically, it is assumed that a swim diaper should be absorbent, or contain urine, like a regular diaper. However, the purpose of a swim diaper is only to contain solid waste; the lack of absorbency prevents the swim diaper from swelling up with water.<ref name="Buying a swim diaper">{{cite web|title=Buying a swim diaper|url=http://www.babycenter.ca/a567958/buying-a-swim-diaper|publisher=The Baby Center|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Pregnancy, Birth and Babies – Myths and Misconceptions |url=https://babymommablog.com/ |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Swimming Nappies Explained |url=https://www.babypaddlers.co.uk/blog/swimming-nappies-explained/ |accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref>
==Types== Often reusable swim diapers are lined with a fiber which encourages the solid waste to cling to the fiber without an absorbency layer. A snug fit in the legs and waist are key to function. Brands such as [[Splash About International|Splash About]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thebusinessdesk.com/northwest/news/202320-energize-splashes-out-on-baby-swimwear-firn.html|title=Energize splashes out on baby swimwear firm {{!}} TheBusinessDesk.com|date=2011-08-04|work=North West|access-date=2018-07-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> and [[The Honest Company|The Honest Co]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/30/travel/airports-get-more-friendly-for-parents-with-young-children.html?_r=0|title=Airports Get More Friendly for Parents With Young Children|access-date=2018-07-29|language=en}}</ref> use tightly knit [[polyester]] or [[neoprene]] as their material. The disadvantages of a reusable swim diaper is that they must be washed to be reused. On the other hand, a disposable swim diaper is only partially [[biodegradable]] and repeated purchases may cost more than reuse. One brand of disposable swim diapers is Little Swimmers, marketed under the [[Kimberly-Clark]] [[Huggies]] brand. [[Procter & Gamble]] produces the rival brand [[Pampers]] Splashers. Both are sold in three sizes: small (16–26&nbsp;lb or 7–12&nbsp;kg), medium (24–34&nbsp;lb or 11–15&nbsp;kg) and large (over 32&nbsp;lb or 14&nbsp;kg+). Due to their design for swimwear, they are not as absorbent and not intended for regular diapering.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
==Swim diapers at public pools== Some public pools require swim diapers for use by young children and the incontinent out of hygiene concerns. For the same reason, other pools do not allow swim diapers at all. Sick children who are not potty-trained and do not wear swim diapers may be responsible for the transmission of [[e. coli infection|e. coli]] from fecal matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essortment.com/family/ecolibabyswim_sont.htm |title=Prevent e.coli with swim diapers |publisher=Essortment.com |date= |accessdate=2010-09-08}}</ref><ref name="Swim diapers may not keep pool water clean, UF experts say">{{cite web|title=Swim diapers may not keep pool water clean, UF experts say|url=http://news.ufl.edu/archive/2007/07/swim-diapers-may-not-keep-pool-water-clean-uf-experts-say.html|publisher=University of Florida|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref>
When not used properly, or when using inferior products, health experts caution that swim diapers may not protect pool water against communicable diseases, such as [[norovirus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ufl.edu/2007/07/10/swim-diaper/ |title=University of Florida News - Swim diapers may not keep pool water clean, UF experts say |publisher=News.ufl.edu |date=2007-07-10 |accessdate=2010-09-08}}</ref>
